# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adenosine-triphosphate
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] For certain uses as a food additive, propylene glycol is considered as GRAS by the US Food and Drug Administration, and is approved for food manufacturing.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In the European Union, it has E-number E1520 for food applications.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] For cosmetics and pharmacology, the number is E490.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is also present in propylene glycol alginate, which is known as E405.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is approved and used as a vehicle for topical, oral, and some intravenous pharmaceutical preparations in the US and Europe.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The compound is sometimes called (alpha) **α-propylene glycol** to distinguish it from the isomer propane-1,3-diol, known as (beta) β-propylene glycol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Commercial processes typically use the racemate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The S-isomer is produced by biotechnological routes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Industrially, propylene glycol is mainly produced from propylene oxide (for food-grade use).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] According to a 2018 source, 2.16 M tonnes are produced annually.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Manufacturers use either non-catalytic high-temperature process at 200 °C (392 °F) to 220 °C (428 °F), or a catalytic method, which proceeds at 150 °C (302 °F) to 180 °C (356 °F) in the presence of ion exchange resin or a small amount of sulfuric acid or alkali.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Final products contain 20% propylene glycol, 1.5% of dipropylene glycol, and small amounts of other polypropylene glycols.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Further purification produces finished industrial grade or USP/JP/EP/BP grade propylene glycol that is typically 99.5% or greater.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Use of USP (US Pharmacopoeia) propylene glycol can reduce the risk of Abbreviated New Drug Application (ANDA) rejection.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol can also be obtained from glycerol, a byproduct from the production of biodiesel.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] This starting material is usually reserved for industrial use because of the noticeable odor and taste that accompanies the final product.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] (S)-Propanediol is synthesized via fermentation methods.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Lactic acid and lactaldehyde are common intermediates.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Dihydroxyacetone phosphate, one of the two products of breakdown (glycolysis) of fructose 1,6-bisphosphate, is a precursor to methylglyoxal.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] This conversion is the basis of a potential biotechnological route to the commodity chemical 1,2-propanediol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Three-carbon deoxysugars are also precursor to the 1,2-diol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Forty-five percent of propylene glycol produced is used as a chemical feedstock for the production of unsaturated polyester resins.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In this regard, propylene glycol reacts with a mixture of unsaturated maleic anhydride and isophthalic acid to give a copolymer.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] This partially unsaturated polymer undergoes further crosslinking to yield thermoset plastics.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Related to this application, propylene glycol reacts with propylene oxide to give oligomers and polymers that are used to produce polyurethanes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is used in water-based acrylic architectural paints to extend dry time which it accomplishes by preventing the surface from drying due to its slower evaporation rate compared to water.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In regulated amounts, propylene glycol is designated as safe for food manufacturing as an anticaking agent, emulsifier, flavor agent, humectant, texturizer, stabilizer, solvent, antioxidant, antimicrobial agent, and thickener.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The European Food Safety Authority authorizes propylene glycol for use in food manufacturing, establishing a safe daily intake of 25 mg per kg of body weight.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Specifically for ice cream or ice milk products, Health Canada permits use of propylene glycol mono fatty acid esters as an emulsifier and stabilizer at a maximum level of use of 0.35% of the ice cream made from the ingredients mix.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is used in a variety of other edible items, such as baked goods, desserts, prepared meals, flavoring mixes, candy, popcorn, whipped dairy products, and soda.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] It is also used in beer to stabilize the foam.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Vaporizers used for delivery of pharmaceuticals or personal-care products often include propylene glycol among the ingredients.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In alcohol-based hand sanitizers, it is used as a humectant to prevent the skin from drying.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is used as a solvent in many pharmaceuticals, including oral, injectable, and topical formulations.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Many pharmaceutical drugs which are insoluble in water utilize propylene glycol as a solvent and carrier; benzodiazepine tablets are one example.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is also used as a solvent and carrier for many pharmaceutical capsule preparations.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Additionally, certain formulations of artificial tears use propylene glycol as an ingredient.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The freezing point of water is depressed when mixed with propylene glycol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] It is used as aircraft de-icing and anti-icing fluid.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Normally, such time-frame is limited to 15–90 minutes, depending on the severity of snowfall and outside air temperature.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Water-propylene glycol mixtures dyed pink to indicate the mixture is relatively nontoxic are sold under the name of RV or marine antifreeze.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is frequently used as a substitute for ethylene glycol in low toxicity, environmentally friendly automotive antifreeze.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] It is also used to winterize the plumbing systems in vacant structures.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The eutectic composition/temperature is 60:40 propylene glycol:water/−60 °C.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The −50 °F/−45 °C commercial product is, however, water rich; a typical formulation is 40:60.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol, vegetable glycerin, or a mixture of both, are the main ingredients in e-liquid used in electronic cigarettes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] They are aerosolized to resemble smoke and serve as carriers for substances such as nicotine and flavorants.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] When used in average quantities, propylene glycol has no measurable effect on development and/or reproduction on animals and probably does not adversely affect human development or reproduction without active use.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The safety of electronic cigarettes—which use propylene glycol-based preparations of nicotine or THC and other cannabinoids—is the subject of much controversy.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Vitamin E acetate has also been identified in this controversy.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The acute oral toxicity of propylene glycol is very low, and large quantities are required to cause perceptible health effects in humans; in fact, the toxicity of propylene glycol is one third that of ethanol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] According to the Dow Chemical Company, the LD50 (dose that kills 50% of the test population) for rats is 20 g/kg (oral/rat).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Toxicity generally occurs at plasma concentrations over 4 g/L, which requires extremely high intake over a relatively short period of time, or when used as a vehicle for drugs or vitamins given intravenously or orally in large bolus doses.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] It would be nearly impossible to reach toxic levels by consuming foods or supplements, which contain at most, by mass, one per mille of PG, except for alcoholic beverages in the US, which are allowed five percent by mass.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Cases of propylene glycol poisoning are usually related to either inappropriate intravenous administration or accidental ingestion of large quantities.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The potential for long-term oral toxicity is also low.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In a National Toxicology Program continuous breeding study, no effects on fertility were observed in male or female mice that received propylene glycol in drinking water at doses up to 10100 mg/kg bw/day.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] No effects on fertility were seen in either the first or second generation of treated mice.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In a two-year study, 12 rats were provided with feed containing as much as 5% propylene glycol, and showed no apparent ill effects.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol may be non-irritating to the skin, see section Allergic reaction below for details on allergic reactions.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Undiluted propylene glycol is minimally irritating to the eye, producing slight transient conjunctivitis; the eye recovers after the exposure is removed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol has not caused sensitization or carcinogenicity in laboratory animal studies, nor has it demonstrated genotoxic potential.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Inhalation of propylene glycol vapors appears to present no significant hazard in ordinary applications.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Due to the lack of chronic inhalation data, it is recommended that propylene glycol not be used in inhalation applications such as theatrical productions, or antifreeze solutions for emergency eye wash stations.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Recently, propylene glycol (commonly alongside glycerol) has been included as a carrier for nicotine and other additives in e-cigarette liquids, the use of which presents a novel form of exposure.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The potential hazards of chronic inhalation of propylene glycol or the latter substance as a whole are as-yet unknown.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] This concentration has been linked to use of water-based paints and water-based system cleansers.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] However, the study authors write that glycol ethers and not propylene glycol are the likely culprit.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Studies with intravenously administered propylene glycol have resulted in LD50 values in rats and rabbits of 7 mL/kg BW.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Ruddick (1972) also summarized intramuscular LD50 data for rat as 13–20 mL/kg BW, and 6 mL/kg BW for the rabbit.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Adverse effects to intravenous administration of drugs that use propylene glycol as an excipient have been seen in a number of people, particularly with large bolus dosages.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Responses may include CNS depression, "hypotension, bradycardia, QRS and T abnormalities on the ECG, arrhythmia, cardiac arrhythmias, seizures, agitation, serum hyperosmolality, lactic acidosis, and haemolysis".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] A high percentage (12–42%) of directly-injected propylene glycol is eliminated or secreted in urine unaltered depending on dosage, with the remainder appearing in its glucuronide-form.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The speed of renal filtration decreases as dosage increases, which may be due to propylene glycol's mild anesthetic / CNS-depressant properties as an alcohol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] In one case, intravenous administration of propylene glycol-suspended nitroglycerin to an elderly man may have induced coma and acidosis.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] However, no confirmed lethality from propylene glycol was reported.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is an approved food additive for dog and sugar glider food under the category of animal feed and is generally recognized as safe for dogs, with an LD50 of 9 mL/kg.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The LD50 is higher for most laboratory animals (20 mL/kg).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] However, it is prohibited for use in food for cats due to links to Heinz body formation and a reduced lifespan of red blood cells.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Heinz body formation from MPG has not been observed in dogs, cattle, or humans.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Estimates on the prevalence of propylene glycol allergy range from 0.8% (10% propylene glycol in aqueous solution) to 3.5% (30% propylene glycol in aqueous solution).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The North American Contact Dermatitis Group (NACDG) data from 1996 to 2006 showed that the most common site for propylene glycol contact dermatitis was the face (25.9%), followed by a generalized or scattered pattern (23.7%).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Investigators believe that the incidence of allergic contact dermatitis to propylene glycol may be greater than 2% in patients with eczema or fungal infections, which are very common in countries with lesser sun exposure and lower-than-normal vitamin D balances.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Therefore, propylene glycol allergy is more common in those countries.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Because of its potential for allergic reactions and frequent use across a variety of topical and systemic products, propylene glycol was named the American Contact Dermatitis Society's Allergen of the Year for 2018.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Recent publication from The Mayo Clinic reported 0.85% incidence of positive patch tests to propylene glycol (100/11,738 patients) with an overall irritant rate of 0.35% (41/11,738 patients) during a 20-year period of 1997–2016.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] 87% of the reactions were classified as weak and 9% as strong.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The positive reaction rates were 0%, 0.26%, and 1.86% for 5%, 10%, and 20% propylene glycol respectively, increasing with each concentration increase.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] The irritant reaction rates were 0.95%, 0.24%, and 0.5% for 5%, 10%, and 20% propylene glycol, respectively.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol occurs naturally, probably as the result of anaerobic catabolism of sugars in the human gut.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] It is degraded by vitamin B12-dependent enzymes, which convert it to propionaldehyde.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is expected to degrade rapidly in water from biological processes, but is not expected to be significantly influenced by hydrolysis, oxidation, volatilization, bioconcentration, or adsorption to sediment.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol is readily biodegradable under aerobic conditions in freshwater, in seawater and in soil.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Therefore, propylene glycol is considered as not persistent in the environment.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Propylene glycol exhibits a low degree of toxicity toward aquatic organisms.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Several guideline studies available for freshwater fish with the lowest observed lethal concentration of 96-h LC50 value of 40,613 mg/L in a study with *Oncorhynchus mykiss*.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Similarly, the lethal concentration determined in marine fish is a 96-h LC50 of >10,000 mg/L in *Scophthalmus maximus*.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Although propylene glycol has low toxicity, it exerts high levels of biochemical oxygen demand (BOD) during degradation in surface waters.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] This process can adversely affect aquatic life by consuming oxygen needed by aquatic organisms for survival.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1-2-propanediol] Large quantities of dissolved oxygen (DO) in the water column are consumed when microbial populations decompose propylene glycol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In 1858 a batch of sweets in Bradford, England, was accidentally adulterated with poisonous arsenic trioxide.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] About five pounds (two kilograms) of sweets were sold to the public, leading to around 20 deaths and over 200 people suffering the effects of arsenic poisoning.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The adulteration of food had been practised in Britain since before the Middle Ages, but in the nineteenth century, with increasing urbanisation and the rise in shop-purchased food, adulterants became a growing problem.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] With the cost of sugar high, replacing it with substitutes was common.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] For the sweets produced in Bradford, the confectioner was supposed to purchase powdered gypsum, but a mistake at the wholesale chemist meant arsenic was purchased instead.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Three men were arrested—the chemist who sold the arsenic, his assistant and the sweet maker—but all three were acquitted after the judge decided it was all accidental and there was no case for any of them to answer.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The deaths led to the Adulteration of Food or Drink Act 1860, although the legislation was criticised for being too ambiguous and the penalties for breaching it too low to act as a deterrent.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The deaths were also a factor in the passage of the Pharmacy Act 1868.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Cost was the reason adulterants were used; sugar, for example, cost 6½d per pound; the adulterant cost ½d per pound.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The adulteration fell into three categories: firstly were harmless additions, such as chicory in coffee, adding flour to mustard and watering down milk.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] More serious were the addition of indigestible ingredients, including introducing alum, gypsum or chalk into white bread or tree or shrub leaves into tea leaves.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Finally, dangerous additions to foods included salts of copper and red lead glaze used as colourants, mercury salts added to cheese, and the use of arsenic, sulphuric acid and nitric acid.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The chemist Arthur Hill Hassall was prominent in the field of food analysis as an analytical microscopist who established levels of adulteration.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Between 1850 and 1856 he examined 3,000 samples of food and found 65 per cent of them contained adulterants.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Those involved in adulterating foodstuff used nicknames to hide the practice.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] These included "daff", "duck", "duff", "derby", "multum", "flash" and "stuff".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] One local name used in Bradford—an industrial town in the West Riding of Yorkshire—was "daft".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In the Victorian era, arsenic was an ingredient in several household products, including medicines (for external and internal use), candles, wallpaper, soft furnishings and colourants for foods.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It was also used as a poison for murder.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] So many people died of arsenic poisoning—both deliberate and accidental—that legislation in the form of the Arsenic Act 1851 was introduced; it was the first piece of UK legislation to attempt to control the sale of a poisonous substance.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It stated that arsenic should only be sold to adults, the sale recorded in a book—signed by both seller and buyer—and that there should be a witness to the sale if the buyer was unknown to the seller.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Any arsenic not to be used for medicinal purposes was to be coloured with soot or indigo to differentiate it from other white powders on sale.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] There was no restriction on who could sell arsenic; no licence was required and any trader was able to sell it as long as they kept a record of the sale.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Although the act controlled the method of sale, it did not bring an end to arsenic-related problems or the widespread use of arsenic in household goods.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Arsenic trioxide—also known as white arsenic—is an industrially produced inorganic compound with the formula As 2O 3.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It is white and is commonly found in either powdered or crystal form—the latter resembling sugar or sand.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] It is used as a wood preservative and a pesticide.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] As a solid it is tasteless, but when in solution, it is described as "very faint, at first sweetish, afterward very slightly metallic".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] William Hardaker, known to locals as "Humbug Billy", sold sweets from a stall in the Greenmarket in central Bradford.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Hardaker purchased his confectionery from Joseph Neal, who made the sweets in Stone Street a few hundred yards to the north.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The sweets were peppermint lozenges, made by mixing peppermint oil into a base of sugar, water and gum, which was made into a paste, then dried on boards before being cut into lozenge shapes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] As the sugar was relatively expensive, Neal would substitute some of the sugar with powdered gypsum; he later justified his actions by saying "where I use a pound of it, there are people who will use a ton of it".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In the week before the regular Saturday market, Neal was due to make a batch of lozenges for Hardaker but had run out of "daft".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neal asked his lodger, James Archer, to visit a druggist in the town of Shipley, five miles (eight kilometres) by road, to purchase the gypsum.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The druggist, Charles Hodgson, was ill in bed; his assistant, William Goddard, was on duty and had been told the daft was in a barrel in the attic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard had only been working for Hodgson for a few weeks, hoping for an apprenticeship.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When Archer asked for the daft, Goddard went to the attic and took twelve pounds (five kilograms) of powder from a cask.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard did not realise that there were two identical barrels and he had taken powder from a barrel of arsenic trioxide; the barrel was only labelled as such on the base.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neal employed James Appleton—an experienced sweetmaker—to manufacture the lozenges.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Both men thought the new batch of sweets was different from normal: Appleton thought the mixture was more free-flowing and smoother than normal, and both considered the end product was a darker shade than they were used to.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Appleton, working closely with the arsenic, fell ill and suffered from fits of vomiting; Neal, who occasionally tasted the lozenges to check the quality, also began vomiting.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neither man connected their sickness to the lozenges.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When Hardaker collected the sweets from Neal on 30 October 1858 he also noted the different colour from the normal batches.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] He negotiated the lower price of 7+1⁄2d per pound for forty pounds (eighteen kilograms), a discount of 1⁄2d per pound on his usual price.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Hardaker sold the sweets for two ounces (fifty-seven grams) for 1+1⁄2d.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] He ate some of the sweets and by 5:30 pm he became ill; he went home and left his assistant to look after the stall until it closed at 11:30 pm, by which point about a thousand sweets had been sold.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] On the Sunday morning the local police were informed of the deaths of a man named Elijah Wright and two boys, aged 9 and 14, the sons of John Scott; it was thought that the cause of the deaths was cholera.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The misdiagnosis of cholera instead of arsenic poisoning was a common mistake, as the symptoms for both—vomiting, abdominal pain and diarrhoea—were similar and England was affected by an ongoing cholera pandemic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When more deaths were reported during the course of Sunday, Police Constable Campbell was sent to investigate; he made the connection between the sweets and the deaths, and visited Hardaker, seizing the remaining stock, which was just under thirty-six pounds (sixteen kilograms).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Campbell then went to Neal's premises and seized six ounces (one hundred and seventy grams) of fragments of the sweets.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] A detective, William Burniston, went to Shipley with Archer to visit Hodgson, the druggist.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] When Archer indicated the cask from which the powder had been dispensed, Hodgson immediately identified it as containing arsenic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Burniston arrested Goddard, the assistant.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The chief constable, William Leveratt, had been kept abreast of developments, and deployed men to local inns and alehouses to spread warnings about the lozenges.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] He sent out bellmen to announce the warnings across the town and, at 11 pm, he had warning notices printed up and posted overnight for people to see in the morning.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] A local doctor, John Henry Bell, hypothesised the poisonings of his patients were caused by arsenic; he gave the lozenges from one patient to an analytical chemist, who confirmed his theory.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Bell treated sixty patients for the poisoning.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] By midday on the Monday—1 November—the number of dead had risen to twelve, with seventy-eight people seriously ill.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Police visited Neal for a second time and searched his premises more thoroughly, finding hundreds of fragments still on the drying boards used when preparing the lozenges.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Neal's wife also admitted that she had found other fragments and thrown them onto the fire; she had also been to their own sweetshop and brought back some bags of mixed sweets that contained lozenges or lozenge fragments.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] While the police were there, Neal ran off and was pursued; he was found sitting in his kitchen at home.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard was brought in front of the magistrates on the Monday; he was remanded in custody.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] An inquest was opened the following day.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The magistrates also met and decided that Hodgson should also be arrested and remanded.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] On Wednesday the magistrates also decided that Neal should also be arrested, although he was released on bail.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] They heard from an analytical chemist, Felix Rimmington, who estimated that each sweet contained nine grains (580 mg) of arsenic; he added that four and a half grains were sufficient to kill an adult male.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Rimmington later made an analysis of the lozenges which showed each contained between eleven and sixteen grains (710 and 1,040 mg).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] By the end of Wednesday, fifteen people had been reported dead, eleven of whom were children; thirteen more were listed as "dangerously ill", and another hundred and fifty were ill but not in danger.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The magistrates met again on the Friday and determined that the three men in custody should be sent to the next York assizes for trial on a charge of manslaughter by negligence.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Bail for Hodgson and Neal was set at £200; that for Goddard was set at £100.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The number of dead had risen to seventeen, with 196 people ill.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Eventually up to twenty-one people died and over two hundred were sick; figures on the number of deaths vary, with either twenty or twenty-one people dead.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The assizes opened on 9 December 1858; the judge was Mr Baron Warren.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] In his opening remarks he said that there was no case for Neal to answer as he was not present when the arsenic was purchased or when the lozenges were made, and dismissed the case against him.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Goddard, Warren said, was only following the instructions of his master and so also had no case to answer; his case was also dismissed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Warren said the case against Hodgson should stand and that he would be tried later in the month.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Hodgson's trial opened on 21 December 1858 for the manslaughter of Elizabeth Mary Midgley, a seven-year-old girl.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] If he was found guilty of the charge, others would follow.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] After hearing some of the evidence, the judge stopped the proceedings and said there was no case for Hodgson to answer; he instructed the jury to record a verdict of not guilty, which they did.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The deaths led to calls for legislation to stop similar events occurring, and the Adulteration of Food or Drink Act 1860 was passed into law, "on a wave of public revulsion" against the event at Bradford, according to the microbiologist John Postgate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] According to the legal scholar Jillian London, "Although the Bradford incident was far from solely responsible for the passage of the 1860 Act, it was instrumental in heightening public awareness of and outrage towards adulteration".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The political economist Sébastien Rioux observes that the law only applied when adulterated food was being passed off as pure, so the protection was only on misrepresenting what was being sold, rather than ensuring the purity of all food.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Whorton considers the Act "was next to useless" as its provisions were too ambiguous and the penalties for breaching it—at £5—were too low to act as a deterrent.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] The events at Bradford were still felt ten years later when the Pharmacy Act 1868 was passed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1858-bradford-sweets-poisoning] Legislation on pharmacies was considered from 1859 onwards, although the Royal Pharmaceutical Society opposed a Poison Bill in 1859.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In 1900, more than 6,000 people in England were poisoned by arsenic-tainted beer, with more than 70 of the affected dying as a result.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The food safety crisis was caused by arsenic entering the supply chain through impure sugar which had been made with contaminated sulphuric acid.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The illness was prevalent across the Midlands and North West England, with Manchester being the most heavily affected.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Originally misdiagnosed as alcoholic neuropathy, the main epidemic was only recognised after several months.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Additionally, investigation into the outbreak found other sources of arsenic in beer, which had been unknowingly poisoning thousands in decades preceding the outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This mass poisoning is unusual in that it was not noticed for four months.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The doctors, seeing patients who were usually heavy drinkers and who showed muscle weakness and numbness of the hands or feet, initially thought that the patients had "alcoholic neuritis".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Nevertheless, a marked increase in the number of cases was noted, with 41 people succumbing to peripheral neuritis, multiple neuritis or alcoholic neuritis and 66 people perishing from alcoholism in the four months of the outbreak, while the previous seven months revealed only 22.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] These cases of neuritis were eventually connected to cases of skin discolouration previously thought to be unrelated.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Ernest Reynolds, the doctor responsible for making the connection, also noted that only one substance would cause these symptoms: arsenic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] He also noted that heavy drinkers who drank mainly spirits seemed less affected than beer drinkers.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] He gathered samples for analysis from the taverns frequented by his patients, which confirmed the presence of arsenic in the beer they consumed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Once the breweries affected were identified, investigation as to where the arsenic came from were instituted.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] It was found that the arsenic was present in invert sugar provided to the breweries by Bostock & Co. of Garston.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] To lower costs in the tight-margin English beer market, some breweries substituted high-quality barley malt with low-quality barley malt supplemented with sugar.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This practice was somewhat controversial; as part of the Pure Beer movement, an inquiry on the use of brewing substitutes had been called.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This inquiry, starting in 1896 and ending in 1899, had concluded that brewing substitutes were not "deleterious materials" under the Sale of Food and Drugs Act 1875 (38 & 39 Vict. c.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] 63) and that further legislation was not required.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This sugar was made by acid hydrolysis of starch, where starch is heated in the presence of an acid to form glucose.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Such a method was not new, and had been employed commercially since at least 1814.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Bostock & Co. used sulphuric acid to perform the acid hydrolysis.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This acid, purchased from Nicholson & Sons, was made from pyrites which contained arsenic, which remained in the final product.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] John Nicholson & Sons, of Leeds, had provided sulphuric acid to Bostock & Co. since 1888.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] For most of the length of the business relationship, the acid provided was free from arsenic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] However, in March 1900, Nicholson started supplying unpurified sulphuric acid containing arsenic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This practice continued until November 1900, when the acid was found to be the cause of the outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Nicholson claimed that they did not know the nature of Bostock's use of the acid, and that they could have provided arsenic-free acid if requested.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Once the main source of the outbreak had been identified as arsenic poisoning, further investigation into arsenic contamination of beer was undertaken.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Eventually, it was found that arsenic was also introduced into beer by the malted barley.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In the kilning stage of malting, the barley humidity content is reduced by drying the grain with the hot vapours of a fire, usually fuelled by coke or coal.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] It was found that when arsenic is present in the fuel, it could then be deposited upon the barley before steeping, and therefore would be present in the final product.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Investigation into the outbreak uncovered that most cases of alcoholic neuropathy endemic to Manchester were, in fact, misdiagnosed arsenic poisoning, with this alternative route being responsible for the poisoning of thousands in the years preceding the outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Such contamination was tied to an outbreak in the borough of Halifax in January and February 1902 where 13 to 14 cases of arsenic poisoning were noted, three deadly.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The malt was dried over a non-sequestered gas coke fire, thus resulting in contaminated beer.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] After the cause of the poisoning was reported by the media, a considerable reduction in beer consumption was noted in the region.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The response from the brewing industry was mixed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] There was a strong, immediate reaction from some breweries, led by the large Manchester brewery Groves and Whitnall, who went as far as sending out telegrams to all the taverns and inns that had purchased their beer.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Breweries disposed of thousands of barrels of beer by dumping them in the city's sewers.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Other breweries were slower to respond, with fines being handed out to breweries whose beer samples could still be purchased by investigators.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Additionally, one pub was fined for selling contaminated beer after they were notified of the presence of arsenic by the manufacturer.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In Lancashire, 23 taverns and pubs were prosecuted for violations under section 6 of the Sale of Food and Drugs Act 1875.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Bostock & Co. went into liquidation, and sued Nicholson & Sons for damages, for breach of an implied condition under the Sale of Goods Act 1893.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Nicholson & Sons survived, and was later acquired by B.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The poisoning resulted in the appointment of a Royal Commission led by Lord Kelvin, which submitted a preliminary report in 1901 and a final report in 1903.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] The effects on the beer market were short-lived, and consumption of beer resumed over the course of the year.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] Attempts to revive the pure beer movement were nullified by the commission's report, and by the fact that arsenic was present in malted barley as well as sugar.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] There seemed to be no direct effects on legislation resulting from the incident.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] In 1901, a considerable decline in the birth rate was noted in Manchester, Salford and Liverpool.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] This decline was greater in areas most affected, leading the Royal Commission to conclude that the epidemic was the cause.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1900-english-beer-poisoning] A 2026 study found, "the arsenic-in-beer epidemic caused a 10% drop in births in 1901, but the effect was short-lived.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The **1971 Iraq poison grain disaster** was a mass methylmercury poisoning incident where seed grain treated with a methylmercury fungicide, which was never intended for human consumption, was imported into Iraq from Mexico and the United States.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Due to factors like foreign-language labeling and distribution too late into the growing cycle, this toxic grain was consumed as food by Iraqi residents in rural areas of the country.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Sufferers experienced paresthesia (numbness of skin), ataxia (lack of coordination of muscle movements) and vision loss, symptoms similar to those observed in Minamata disease-affected Japan.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Though the official death toll was 459, figures of as much as ten times greater have been suggested.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] When it occurred in 1971, the poisoning was the largest mercury poisoning event in history, with cases peaking in February 1972 and stopping by the end of March.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Reports after the disaster recommended tighter regulation, better labelling and handling of mercury-treated grain, and wider involvement of the World Health Organization in monitoring and preventing poisoning incidents.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Investigation confirmed the particular danger posed to fetuses and young children.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The properties of mercury make it an effective fungicide.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Methylmercury had been banned in Sweden in 1966, the first country to do so, and the United Kingdom followed in 1971.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Previous mercury-poisoning incidents had occurred in Iraq in 1956 and 1960.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In 1956, there had been around 200 cases, and 70 deaths; in 1960 there had been 1000 cases and 200 deaths, in both cases due to ethylmercury compounds.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Among the recommendations made after the 1960 incident had been to colour any toxic grain for easy identification.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Before the 1971 incident, around 200–300 cases of methylmercury poisoning had been reported worldwide.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Drought had reduced harvests in 1969, affecting 500,000 people, and in 1970.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some 95,000 tonnes (93,000 long tons; 105,000 short tons) of grain (73,202 tonnes of wheat grain and 22,262 tonnes of barley), coloured a pink-orange hue, were shipped to Iraq from the United States and Mexico.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The wheat arrived in Basra on SS *Trade Carrier* between 16 September and 15 October, the barley between 22 October and 24 November 1971.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Iraq's government chose Mexipak, a high-yield wheat seed developed in Mexico by Norman Borlaug.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The seeds contained an average of 7.9 μg/g of mercury, with some samples containing up to nearly twice that.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The three northern governorates of Nineveh, Kirkuk and Erbil received more than half the shipments.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Contributing factors to the epidemic included the fact that distribution started late, and much grain arrived after the October–November planting season.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Farmers were supposed to plant the poisoned grain, but many instead offered it to their families as food, since their own planting had been completed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Distribution was, in later stages hurried and open, with grain being distributed free of charge with the expectation of payment in kind when the harvest season came.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some farmers even sold off their own grain, in order to claim more of the imported grain.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This left them dependent on tainted grain for the winter.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Many Iraqis were either unaware of the significant health risk posed, or chose to ignore the warnings.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Initially, farmers were to certify with a thumbprint or signature that they understood the grain was poison, however some distributors ignored this requirement.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Warnings on the sacks were in Spanish and English, not at all understood, or included the black-and-white skull and crossbones design, which meant nothing to Iraqis.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The long, asymptomatic latent period of mercury poisoning may have granted farmers a false sense of security when animals fed the grain initially appeared to be fine.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The red dye washed off the grain; the mercury did not.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Hence, washing may have given only the appearance of removing the poison.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The Iraqi government made limited attempts to control the distribution of the mercury grain.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Four high ranking officials were posted at the Basra docks during the first two weeks of unloading.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] However, control of the unloading process slipped afterwards, with some spilt grain being stolen by dockworkers.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Aircraft were used to drop half a million leaflets warning of the mercury, however this was an insufficient quantity for the population at the time.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Ground seed dust inhalation was a contributing factor in farmers during sowing and grinding.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Consumption of ground grain in homemade bread is thought to have been the major source of toxicity, since no cases were reported in urban areas, where government flour supplies were commercially regulated.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The effect of mercury took some time – the latent period between ingestion and the first symptoms (typically paresthesia – numbness in the extremities) was between 16 and 38 days.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Paresthesia was the predominant symptom in less serious cases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Worse cases included ataxia (typically loss of balance), blindness or reduced vision, and death resulting from central nervous system failure.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Anywhere between 20 and 40 mg of mercury has been suggested as sufficient for paresthesia (between 0.5 and 0.8 mg/kg of body weight).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] On average, individuals affected consumed 20 kg or so of bread; the 73,000 tonnes provided would have been sufficient for over 3 million cases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The hospital in Kirkuk received large numbers of patients with symptoms that doctors recognised from the 1960 outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The first case of alkylmercury poisoning was admitted to hospital on 21 December.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] By 26 December, the hospital had issued a specific warning to the government.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] By January 1972, the government had started to strongly warn the populace against eating the grain, although dispatches did not mention the large numbers already ill.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The Iraqi Army soon ordered disposal of the grain and eventually declared anyone found selling it would receive the death penalty.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Farmers dumped their supplies wherever possible, contaminating the water supply (particularly the Tigris).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The government initiated a news blackout and released little information about the outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The World Health Organization assisted the Iraqi government through the supply of drugs, analytical equipment and expertise.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Many new treatments were tried, since existing methods for heavy metal poisoning were not particularly effective.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Dimercaprol was administered to several patients, but caused rapid deterioration of their condition.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It was ruled out as a treatment for this sort of poisoning following the outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Polythiol resins, penicillamine and dimercaprol sulfonate all helped, but are believed to have been largely insignificant in overall recovery and outcomes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Dialysis was tested on a few patients late in the treatment period, but they showed no clinical improvement.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The result of all treatments was varied, with some patients' blood mercury level being dramatically reduced, but a negligible effect in others.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] All patients received periods of treatment interspersed with lay periods; continuous treatment was suggested in future cases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Later treatment was less effective in reducing blood toxicity.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] 6,530 patients were admitted to hospitals with poisoning, and 459 deaths were reported.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Cases reached a peak of hundreds per day in January, and had largely subsided by the beginning of March.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Admissions represented every age and gender stratum, although those under the age of ten represented a third of admitted cases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This number is "certainly an underestimate", because of the availability of hospital treatment, hospital overcrowding and lack of faith in treatment.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In the most severely affected areas, prevalence was 28% and mortality was 21% of the cases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Some Iraqi doctors believe both the number of cases and fatalities are at least ten times too low, with perhaps 100,000 cases of brain damage.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] One suggested reason for the vast discrepancy between reported and estimated numbers of deaths is the Iraqi custom, common to large parts of the Middle East, for a person to die at home when possible.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Home deaths would not have been recorded.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] A large number of patients with minor symptoms recovered completely; those with more serious symptoms improved.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] This was in contrast to expected outcomes, largely based on analysis of Minamata disease in Japan.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In boys with mercury levels below clinical poisoning, a reduction in school performance was noted, although this correlation could not be confirmed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In infants, the mercury poisoning caused central nervous system damage.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Relatively low doses caused slower development in children, and abnormal reflexes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Different treatments for mercury poisoning have since been developed, and "quiet baby syndrome", characterised by a baby who never cries, is now a recognised symptom of methylmercury-induced brain damage.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Ongoing recommendations of the food regulation authorities have focused on consumption by pregnant women and infant children, noting the particular susceptibility of fetuses and infants to methylmercury poisoning.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Data from Iraq have confirmed that methylmercury can pass to a child *in utero*, and mercury levels were equal to or higher in the newborn child than in the mother.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] In 1974, a joint Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and World Health Organization (WHO) meeting made several recommendations to prevent a similar outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] These included stressing the importance of labelling bags in the local language and with locally understood warning symbols.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The possibility of an additive creating a strong bitter taste was studied.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] The meeting urged governments to strictly regulate methyl- and ethylmercury use in their respective countries, including limiting use to where no other reasonable alternative was available.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It also recommended the involvement of the FAO and WHO in assisting national governments in regulation and enforcement, and the setting up of national poison control centres.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] Over 9–13 November, a Conference on Intoxication due to Alkylmercury-Treated Seed was held in Baghdad.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It supported the recommendations of the FAO/WHO report and suggested that local and national media should publicise outbreaks, including size and symptoms; it considered the distribution of this information crucial.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It also laid out a general plan as to the collection of relevant information from the field and potential analysis for further investigation.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1971-iraq-poison-grain-disaster] It called on national governments to make use of WHO involvement whenever feasible, and absolved world governments in clear terms, saying that "No country should ever feel that any blame will attach to it for allowing an outbreak to occur".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many of these Austrian wines were exported to West Germany, some of them in bulk to be bottled at large-scale West German bottling facilities.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] At these facilities, some Austrian wines were illegally blended into German wines by the importers, resulting in diethylene glycol ending up in some bulk-bottled West German wines.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The scandal was uncovered by wine laboratories performing quality controls on wines sold in West Germany and immediately made headlines worldwide.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The affected wines were immediately withdrawn from the market.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many involved in the scandal were sentenced to prison or heavy fines in Austria and West Germany.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The short-term effect of the scandal was a complete collapse of Austrian wine exports and a total loss of reputation of the entire Austrian wine industry, with a significant adverse impact on the reputation of German wines.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The long-term effect was that the Austrian wine industry focused their production on other wine types than previously, primarily dry white wines instead of sweet wines, and increasingly targeted a higher market segment.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Still, it took the Austrian wine industry over a decade to recover.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Austria also enacted much stricter wine laws.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] At the time of the scandal, West Germany was the most important export market for Austrian wine and had been so for several years, with an increasing trend.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The Austrian wines exported to West Germany were of a similar style to those produced by West Germany itself, meaning semi-sweet and sweet white wines.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] However, many of these Austrian wines were focused on the low-cost segment, priced lower than German wines at the corresponding level of sweetness.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The traditional sweet wines of West Germany and Austria are produced from late harvest grapes, some of them affected by noble rot, and labelled in a hierarchy of Prädikat designations from Kabinett to Trockenbeerenauslese, depending on the ripeness of the grapes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Although sweet reserve (blending a wine with its own must) was allowed for the production of semi-sweet wines, no external sources of sugar were allowed for any wines with a Prädikat designation.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Thus, the production of wines at higher Prädikat levels tends to vary from year to year depending on vintage conditions, and all wines with higher designations sell at a premium price.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many of the affordable sweet wines exported from Austria were blends from different grape varieties, and several of them did not carry any varietal designations, in contrast to the more expensive Prädikat wines of West Germany, which often were produced from Riesling grapes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Some Austrian exporters had entered into long-term contracts with supermarket chains to supply large quantities of wine at a specified quality level in terms of Prädikat.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] These producers encountered problems in some weak vintages, where much of the grape harvest did not reach sufficient ripeness levels.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] At the levels of ripeness that were reached, the wines would be less sweet, less full-bodied, and more acidic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] One vintage plagued by these problems in Austria was 1982.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] It is believed that when this led to insufficient quantities of wine being available to fulfill the contracts, some producers started to search for methods, including illegal ones, to "correct" the wines.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Simple sweetening (also illegal) would not necessarily do the job since it would not sufficiently correct the taste profile of the wine.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] By using diethylene glycol (DEG), it was possible to affect both the impression of sweetness and the body of the wine.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] German wine chemists have stated that it is unlikely that an individual winemaker of a small winery had sufficient chemical knowledge to devise the scheme, implying that the recipe must have been drawn up by a knowledgeable wine chemist consulting for a large-scale producer.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] DEG was otherwise used as an industrial chemical.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Adulteration of products with DEG has led to thousands of deaths worldwide since the first recorded case: the Elixir sulfanilamide incident in 1937.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] DEG was commonly misconceived of as being ethylene glycol, which is what is commonly understood as antifreeze, and is more toxic.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Most of the recalled wines contained up to a few grams of DEG per litre (and many only a fraction of a gram), which meant that dozens of bottles would have to be consumed in a limited period to reach the lethal dose of approximately 40 grams.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] However, in one record-setting wine (a 1981 Welschriesling Beerenauslese from Burgenland), 48 grams per litre was detected, which meant that the consumption of a single bottle could have been lethal.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Also, long-term consumption of DEG is known to damage the kidney, liver, and brain.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The first wine discovered to contain DEG was a 1983 Ruster Auslese from a supermarket in Stuttgart, analysed on June 27, 1985.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Domestic wine fraud involving illegal sweetening had occurred earlier in West Germany and had led to investigations and prosecution of the winemakers involved.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] What made the 1985 findings very different was that a toxic compound had been used, and subsequent sampling indicated that many different bottlings were part of this dangerous adulteration scheme.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Therefore, unlike cases of simple sweetening, the 1985 DEG findings immediately took the proportion of a full-scale scandal requiring action by federal authorities in both West Germany and Austria.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] On July 9, the Federal Ministry of Health in Bonn issued an official health warning against the consumption of Austrian wines.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The findings immediately made headlines in West German media, and from there were cabled out throughout the world.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] From mid-July onward, selling Austrian wine on any export market was almost impossible.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Some countries like Switzerland and France confiscated thousands of bottles, and Japan introduced a ban on the import and sale of all Austrian wines on July 29, 1985.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In many other countries, wine dealers removed Austrian wines from shelves.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] From a pre-1985 level of around 45 million liters per year, exports immediately fell to one-tenth or roughly 4.4 million liters in 1986.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] They stayed at approximately the same level until 1989 and were slightly higher in 1990–97, but still well below pre-1985 levels.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Not until 2001 did the export volume, at just over 50 million liters, match the old level.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] It thus took the Austrian wine industry fifteen years to regain its former position in terms of export volume, despite optimistic predictions from some quarters in Austria that it would all be forgotten in other countries in one year.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In the weeks following the breaking of the scandal, dozens of wine producers and dealers were arrested by Austrian authorities.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The industry's practice of DEG adulteration was traced back to Otto Nadrasky, a 58-year-old chemist and wine consultant from Grafenwörth, Lower Austria.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The first prison sentence, of one and a half years, followed in mid-October.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Many of the adulterated wines were found to originate in Wagram in Lower Austria, where a consulting wine chemist was prosecuted.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] One of the convicted Wagram winemakers, Karl Grill, proprietor of *Firma Gebrüder Grill*, committed suicide after being sentenced.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The Parliament of Austria enacted a stricter wine law on August 29, 1985.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Having seen the immediate collapse of wine exports, the Austrian government rushed this legislation through parliament for it to be in effect before the 1985 harvest.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In West Germany, following a lengthy investigation, six former leading employees of the wholesale dealer and bottler Pieroth were sentenced to fines of one million Deutsche Marks by the *Landgericht* in Koblenz in April 1996.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Further legal action took place over the coming years across West Germany.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The case went through all three tiers of the administrative courts.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] It was finally settled on October 18, 1990, when the Federal Administrative Court of Germany ruled against Pieroth and found that Geißler had the right to issue the list.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Thus, the legal status of the list was a crucial element in the many contract disputes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] As a consequence of the scandal, a total of 27,000,000 litres of wine (corresponding to 36 million bottles or seven months' worth of Austria's total wine exports at the pre-1985 level) had to be destroyed by the West German authorities, which had confiscated or otherwise collected the wine.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Doing this in an environmentally acceptable way proved challenging because DEG was incompatible with sewage treatment plants.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In the end, the wine was disposed of and destroyed by being poured into the ovens of a cement plant as a cooling agent instead of water.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In Austria, it was reported that the wine, mixed with other agents, was used as a road antifreeze in the particularly severe continental winter of February to March 1986.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] The wine scandal has been the subject of many satirical references to Austrian wine inside Austria, in Germany, and beyond, and long after 1985.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] Shortly after the scandal, the Styrian bard Volker Schöbitz composed a polka under the rhyming title *Zum Wohl, Glykol* – "Cheers, glycol".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] *Glykol* was also announced to be the 1985 Word of the Year in West Germany.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] In *The Simpsons* season 1 episode "The Crepes of Wrath", a reference to the scandal is made when two Frenchmen with whom Bart is staying are arrested after putting antifreeze in wine and making Bart drink it.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1985-austrian-diethylene-glycol-wine-scandal] British rock band Half Man Half Biscuit reference the scandal in the song "RSVP" from their 2011 album *90 Bisodol (Crimond)*.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The **1992–1993 Jack in the Box *E. coli* outbreak** occurred when the *Escherichia coli* O157:H7 bacterium (originating from contaminated beef patties) killed 4 children and infected 732 people across four US states.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak involved 73 Jack in the Box restaurants in California, Idaho, Washington, and Nevada, and has been described as "far and away the most infamous food poison outbreak in contemporary history." The majority of the affected were under 10 years old.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] Four children died and 178 others were left with permanent injury including kidney and brain damage.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] On February 10, 1993, newly inaugurated President Bill Clinton participated in a televised town meeting program from the studios of WXYZ-TV in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] He fielded questions from the studio audience as well as studio audiences in Miami, Florida, and Seattle, and responded to questions from the parents of Riley Detwiler – the fourth and final child to die in the *E. coli* outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The wide media coverage and scale of the outbreak were responsible for "bringing the exotic-sounding bacterium out of the lab and into the public consciousness," but it was not the first *E. coli* O157:H7 outbreak resulting from undercooked patties.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] The bacterium had previously been identified in an outbreak of food poisoning in 1982 (traced to undercooked burgers sold by McDonald's restaurants in Oregon and Michigan).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1993-jack-in-the-box-e-coli-outbreak] Before the Jack in the Box incident, there had been 22 documented outbreaks in the United States resulting in 35 deaths.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Odwalla made and marketed unpasteurized fruit juices for the health segment of the juice market.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The Odwalla plant had several food safety issues, many of which arose because Odwalla did not pasteurize its juice.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Tests discovered low levels of *Listeria monocytogenes*, a pathogen that can harm pregnant women, at the Odwalla factory in 1995.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] In response, the company spent several million dollars on upgrading the plant's safety features, and bacteria were reduced to "relatively low levels".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The next year, Dave Stevenson, Odwalla's technical services director who oversaw quality assurance, suggested to Odwalla executives that the company should add a chlorine rinse to guard against bacteria on the skin of processed fruit, supplementing its existing phosphoric acid wash process.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] However, this plan was dropped by Chip Bettle, Odwalla's senior vice president, who feared that the chemicals would harm the fruit and alter the flavor of the juice.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] In a letter to *The New York Times* written on January 5, 1998, Odwalla's director of communications, Christopher C.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Gallagher, wrote that "Odwalla continuously upgraded its manufacturing process in the period leading up to the recall.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Moreover, our primary indicator of overall quality was daily bacteria-level readings, which were relatively low and decreasing in apple juice".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] On October 30, 1996, health officials from the state of Washington informed Odwalla that they had found a link between an outbreak of the *E. coli* O157:H7 bacterium and a batch of Odwalla's fresh apple juice produced on October 7.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] This was confirmed on November 5 and may have resulted from using rotten fruit; one account tells of fruit being used that was highly decayed.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Another possible source of contamination was fallen apples ("grounders") that had come into contact with animal feces and had not been properly cleaned.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Confirmation that the bacteria came from outside the factory was provided when an inspection on November 15 found no evidence of *E. coli* contamination in the facility.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak came as a surprise as the plant had been inspected by the FDA three months earlier, and Odwalla supervisors were not aware that the *E. coli* bacteria could grow in acidic, chilled apple juice.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Based on a recommendation from the FDA, on October 30, Odwalla's Chief Executive Officer Stephen Williamson voluntarily recalled 13 products which contained apple juice from about 4,600 stores.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Carrot and vegetable juices were also recalled the following day as a precautionary measure since they were processed on the same line.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The recall cost the company $6.5 million and took around 48 hours to complete, with almost 200 trucks being dispatched to collect the recalled products.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Odwalla opened a website and a call center to handle consumer questions about the recall.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] As a result of the outbreak, 16-month-old Anna Gimmestad of Greeley, Colorado died from kidney failure, and more than 60 people became sick.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Fourteen children were hospitalized with hemolytic-uremic syndrome, a severe kidney and blood disorder, and were, according to doctors, "likely to have permanent kidney damage and other lasting problems".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] In consequence, Odwalla stock fell by forty percent, and sales of its products dropped by ninety percent.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The company laid off 60 workers, and, at the end of the fiscal year, posted a loss of $11.3 million.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] The outbreak occurred because Odwalla sold unpasteurized fruit juices, though pasteurization had long been standard in the juice industry, claiming that pasteurization alters the flavor and destroys at least 30% of nutrients and enzymes in fruit juice.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Instead, Odwalla relied on washing usable fruit with sanitizing chemicals before pressing.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Odwalla pleaded guilty, and was fined $1.5 million: at the time, the most significant penalty in a food poisoning case in the United States.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] With the judge's permission, Odwalla donated $250,000 of the $1.5 million to fund research in preventing food-borne illnesses.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] William "Bill" Marler represented several children who developed hemolytic-uremic syndrome and suffered severe kidney damage as a result of the outbreak.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Most of the claims were resolved in early 2000, and in addition to the fines, the company spent roughly another $12 million settling the lawsuits from the families whose children were infected.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] To boost sales following the recall, Odwalla reformulated five products to remove their apple juice content and re-released them in November 1996.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/1996-odwalla-e-coli-outbreak] Flash pasteurization, as well as several other safety precautions, were introduced to the manufacturing process, and the juices reappeared on store shelves on December 5, 1996.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:adenosine-triphosphate/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
